ar derivatives. It derived its popularity from the apostle Saint Bartholomew (Matthew 10:3), who was, among other things, the patron saint of tanners, vintners, and butlers.","As an Irish name, it has been used as an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Pharthaláin</b> (see   McFarlane  )."]},{"name":"Bertha","meanings":["German and Hungarian: from the female personal name <i>Bertha</i>(see   Berta  )."]},{"name":"Bertke","meanings":["North German: probably from a pet form of   Berta  ."]}]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Ronald .  It is sometimes used as a given name in its own right."],"variants":[{"name":"Ronald","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Rögnvaldr</i> (composed of <i>regin</i> ‘advice, decision’ (also, ‘the gods’) + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’). This name was regularly used in the Middle Ages in northern England and Scotland, where Scandinavian influence was strong. It is now widespread throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adelheid Berta von Schauenburg was born about 1057 as the daughter of Adolf von Schauenburg. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Adolf von Santersleben II."},"et":{"um 1057–":"umbes 1057–Surnud","1057–Female":"1057–Surnud","1058–1100":"1058–1100","1072–1128":"1072–1128","1087–1128":"1087–1128","1038–Male":"1038–Surnud","1128":"1128","1038":"1038","um 1087":"umbes 1087","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","1100":"1100","1087":"1087","um 1057":"umbes 1057","1072":"1072","ABT 1072":"umbes 1072"},"fi":{"um 1057–":"noin 1057–Kuollut","1057–Female":"1057–Kuollut","1058–1100":"1058–1100","1072–1128":"1072–1128","1087–1128":"1087–1128","1038–Male":"1038–Kuollut","1128":"1128","1038":"1038","um 1087":"noin 1087","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","1100":"1100","1087":"1087","um 1057":"noin 1057","1072":"1072","ABT 1072":"noin 1072"},"fr":{"um 1057–":"environ 1057–Décédée","1057–Female":"1057–Décédée","1058–1100":"